### Expansion, Inheritance, and the Great Clearances  

When the 2nd Duke of Sutherland—**George Leveson‑Gower, 2nd Duke of Sutherland**—inherited the title in 1833, he also inherited a *vast* portfolio of Scottish lands.  Rather than tending to his tenants, he infamously oversaw the **Highland Clearances**, evicting thousands to make way for sheep.  This episode is still taught in Scottish history courses as a cautionary tale of *capitalist ruthlessness* wrapped in a tartan blanket.  

The family’s wealth swelled further when **The 3rd Duke of Sutherland** (George Leveson‑Gower, 3rd Duke) married **Louisa Emilia Gordon**, an heiress with connections to the **British East India Company**.  Their offspring inherited not just titles but also a *global network* of commercial interests, from cotton mills in Manchester to tea plantations in Ceylon.  

